The Nigerian Railway Corporation, has shut down Lagos Mass Transit Train service in Lagos District until further notice due to the coronavirus threat. LEADERSHIP investigation shows that, the Lagos District of the corporation yesterday operated two Lagos Mass Transit Trains from Ijoko and Kajola to Iddo but the return train journey which was expected to depart Iddo by 5:00p.m and 6.30p.m respectively were cancelled abruptly. The Lagos District Manager of the corporation Engr Jerry Oche who confirmed the shutdown of mass transit trains via a text message said “We have shut down all mass transit train service”. Although, no official reason was given for the shutdown of passenger train service, it may not be unconnected with directive of government that federal government parastatals except those that provide essential services should be shut down In a similar development only few staff of the corporation from level 12 and above were seen yesterday loitering around headquarters of the corporation while staff from levels one to twelve were asked to work from home. It was however observed that prior to shut down of passenger train service the trains were crowded with passengers and the social spacing prescribed for gathering in public places to avoid possible contact with people who might have contacted the dreaded virus was not strictly adhered to. Similarly passengers were not screened to provide their identity cards, addresses and dates of birth as earlier announced by management of the corporation. Deputy Director Public Relations of the corporation, Mr.Yakub Mahmmod however said it will be difficult to screen passengers before entering the train from Kajola/Ijoko to Iddo and back due to the porous nature of the railway station along the railway corridor. He posited that screening of passengers, can only be possible at train stations that have one or two entry points. Recalled that management of the corporation, last week issued a statement announcing the stoppage of all passenger train service till further notice but later issued another statement that passenger trains would operate with the condition that passengers should submit themselves for screening